caption: BEST ON THE ISLAND!

This is the best sushi I've eaten in a long time.  I am really picky about food, much more so for my favorite: sushi. This is hands down, no questions asked, the best sushi you can get in the state of Hawaii. Sushi chef was incredible. Order the omakase; it's slightly expensive, but worth every penny and more. Arigatou for an excellent meal.
Impromptu take out lunch. Yum yum !!

I had dinner on New Year's day and got sick right after. I literally had to stay at the toilet for all night. I couldn't sleep from stomachache and nausea. I went to hospital next day. They only offer OMAKASE for dine in and it is not worth the money. I didn't enjoy the meal but I tried my best to enjoy and not try to be mean since we are all going through the hard time. Thr chefs didn't wear gloves and i also saw a chef writing (checking inventory or something) and touch the food after... I wasted $260 for stomachache all night. If you are looking for good quality sushi OMAKASE, go to other places. I am not going back ever again.

Would give this place 0 stars if I could. DO NOT WASTE YOUR MONEY HERE. Having been to many omakases before, I tried hard not to let the location or ambiance sway me and I really gave them a chance but...  We were completely mislead into thinking the $155 omakase would be worth it after seeing reviews on Google and Yelp, but this is THE MOST DISAPPOINTING we have ever had. The quality of the fish was not bad, but the presentation, pacing, service, portions, ratio, everything was TERRIBLE. We literally just received our miso soup and then were handed this pile of confusing fish in the picture and felt rushed to finish our soup. The texture and taste of the rice was so wrong - it crumbled and fell apart in every piece.  I really tried to give this place a chance, but every course was more disappointing than the last. The servers would repeatedly ask the same questions and though our chef was really nice, it was a disaster.  I can’t remember the last time I’ve left a meal this dissatisfied, almost angry, and cheated of money and time. SKIP THIS PLACE!

WOW!!! The omakase here is AMAZING! Try to sit at the counter near chef/owner Ryuji. He makes it fun and educational. Staff is super attentive and fun as well! Highly recommended if you want an awesome meal in Waikiki!
Best sushi ever..... no conversation

The best Sushi ever! You gotta come try this place... hands down way better than Nobu! Red Fatty Snapper is to die for!

Great sashimi, authentic Japanese side dishes, large portions BUT... bad service, way overpriced and incredibly small minded management: we paid $150 + 30 tip and they charged us 15 cents for a paper bag to take out leftovers, how dumb can one get.

Incredible experience at a great value! Sushi Chef Ryuji takes a personal interest in each piece and plate he serves. He graced us with conversation on the background on his fresh ingredients, his training, and his personal flare. The charming personality of Chef Ryuji and his staff left us feeling welcomed and confident.  This is the best sushi experience in Waikiki.

Went for Valentine's Day and found the $155 omakase a RIP off. 5 small dishes and they were served 2 at a time. In and out in 1 hour. The dishes were tasty but value and timing of service was awful. Would never go back again. Wish we spent $400 elsewhere.
There's nothing subtle about this place. Fresh fish. Giant portions. Worth it.
Sushi! So Yum!

A little bizarre finding this place (no sign outside and windows are tinted so much you can’t easily see if they’re open. Once inside, the place was reserved at capacity so was only able to get a 50-minute window. Service was attentive. Next time would grab a reservation to get the complete experience.  Ambience was that of an izakaya—friendly, a bit of conversations flowing all around the restaurant, not at all pretentious.  Got the $75 set omakase (in place of the “open ended” option) at a table. IMHO, if you’re used to “traditional” Edo-mae sushi, this place feels very different. The pieces of sushi are gargantuan (many pieces benefit from being eaten swiftly before the seaweed gets soggy; this was a challenge). But if you’ve ever gone to a sushi spot and worried you’d need to eat after, that should be less of a concern here. There are some delicate touches with pretty generous portions to carry you through. The highlight for me was the isaki “chicken grunt” nigiri, which tasted like a light ono, or even a cross between yellowtail and mackerel—rich while tasting of the sea.  Overall satisfied I tried this place. Would like to compare & contrast with Sushi ii since it’s a block away.

My wife took me here for a date night. Sat at the bar and decided to give their omakase a try. It was one of the best omakase I've ever had. They do not skimp on portions here. I was stuffed after the first half, and was struggling to get the last couple of dishes down. With that said, they were all delicious, I couldn't stop eating. If he had served me more, I would've kept going. It's a small restaurant, but I would definitely recommend getting a seat at the bar & trying their omakase first hand.

Last time we were here was a year ago, and distinctively we can tell the chef has enhanced and refined his already amazing skills.  His passion for food and his guests is what separates this restaurant from others, can't wait to come back!!
Omakase FTW
Masters of their craft. The butter fish roll and spicy tuna roll showed innovative thought behind flavor pairings. Quality seaweed and pickled ginger as well.

I had the omakase at Murayama and I can say I really haven't had anything like it around Hawaii. The fish cuts are really generous and the chef uses interesting flavors to balance the different fishes.

Short version: If you're looking for authentic, delicious raw fish on the island this is your spot. Not cheap, and if you want sushi rolls there are probably cheaper and still delicious options. If you want an experience and a ton of food, I recommend the Omakase.  Longer version: This place is surprisingly hard to find. It's on the third floor, not noticable from the street. Atmosphere is nice, somewhere between casual and dressed up. We sat at the bar and were entertained by the chef all night. The drinks were good, but the food was what we'd come back for. Like I said earlier, it's pricey. It's also worth it. The Omakase is 8-10 courses of small plates. It is almost too much for one person by the end. You get to try so many different types of fish. Everything tasted high quality. Some friends ordered a la cart and their dishes looked delicious. I definitely want to come back here, maybe as a special occasion place when we are craving raw fish.

(it's fried) Be careful with the fish bones, they're a bit of a pain to deal with, but the flavor is worth it.  They also have fun flavors of gelato, like yuzu, black sesame, and condensed milk available for dessert, if you still have room after eating all that delicious food.

I would highly recommend sitting at the sushi bar and getting the omaskase. The way Chef Ryuji gets the flavours of the sushi - I'm still daydreaming about it.  I love Honolulu, and Sushi Murayama is definitely one of the top three reasons to why I want to go back sooner than later.  I would also recommend ordering the sake "by glass" - the way they pour the sake, you really get two glasses out of it... and it's a great way to try different type of sake.  If you are looking for a good sushi spot to taste some quality sushi - I would highly, highly, highly recommend this place.  Trust me - you won't regret it.

Our waiter was very friendly and helpful with recommendations. We got a nice bottle of sake to share between four of us and we elected to go with the omakase. Every bite was just beyond words and all were gone as soon as they were served. By the end of the meal, we were so full but couldn’t help ourselves and kept on eating. Definitely will try to come back here again.
The best sushi place I have been so far. A little pricey, but the food and the presentation is breathtaking. A small and visually pleasing place has a great atmosphere and attentive service.

Absolutely delicious!!! We went twice to this place while our stay in Hawaii. Now I want to come back to Hawaii just to eat there! Must try!!! Sushi is extremely fresh and sooooo tasty!! Everything what I tried was just top notch!!! People are complaining about size of the pieces for me it was a plus! The chef could be cheap and cut tiny pieces for the same price but he wants you to enjoy the fish to the fullest. This actually shows how good the quality of the fish is. You would not be able to eat big pieces if it was poor quality. That's one of the reasons many places cut there pieces very small so that rice and souse will take your attention away and you don't notice how bad the fish is. Prices are very reasonable too looking at the quality and the size. The chef is very friendly and made us feel very comfortable there. He also gave us very detailed info about every order he made, where the fish came from and all that. Great atmosphere. I would recommend this place to anyone who understands good sushi! If you want cheap average sushi that's not a place for you.

Okay. I understand that SOME people might, maybe, have an issue with the size of the fish. That's an extra bite of yummy delicious fish. Excellent sake selection. Fish is superb. And, if you don't want to make decisions, order the Omakase. We were stuffed and everything was amazing. Highly recommend.

The food is amazing! Best sushi I've ever had. Everything was delicious and tasty. All of the fish is cut in front of you and made. Everything just melts in your mouth. The oysters are huge! Biggest oysters I've seen and it is so delicious with the sauce he puts on it, all the fish (blue fin, salmon, white fish ect.) was melt in your mouth and his seasoning/sauce is perfect for every dish, I ended my night with wagyu steak and miso soup.  For the love of sushi, get the wagyu steak! I'm drooling just thinking about it, it melts in your mouth, the flavor is amazing, and it's so soft. I definitely wanted more of it.

Step aside, Jiro! Chef Murayama treats us to one of the most creative Omakase courses available in the US. The base Omakase coming at $75 is well worth its price, especially for its quality and quantity. I cannot accurately predict another customer's experience given another day, but I can say that in the menu, Chef Murayama demonstrates passion and drive to surprise the taster. While maintaining tradition of buying the freshest fish from Japan and locally, I can say every ingredient during the course was carefully picked and matched to the texture and flavor of the seafood. Not to mention, each slice (more like chunk) of fish was gargantuan, complemented by the colorful visual appeal of balanced level of marinade, dressing, and base.  On service, Chef Murayama and his staff are friendly and funny. You'll always hear some hearty laughter with customers. To get the best experience, take a seat at the bar, and you'll be both entertained and made well-informed of the art of seafood.  This is not an experience to be missed when visiting Honolulu. Don't expect to get sushi rolls with cream cheese here. This is for those who want not only an authentic sushi experience, but also take pleasure in seeing museum-quality culinary art and precision seafood engineering.
5 stars, don't remember having such fresh seafood/nigiri. As a non-local, taken by surprise, would definately visit again!

Absolutely divine! If you're the person who understands, appreciates, and genuinely enjoys the skills of an exceptional sushi master, please honor yourself by requesting a seating here. Their menu represents a very good selection as well as their vast drinks list.  Parking is easy, and the atmosphere is welcoming. Service is wonderful! We will be back!

The omakase was one of the best experiences I've ever had. We came right before they were closing for lunch but they were still very accommodating. The chef was friendly and prepared all of the dishes perfectly. The fish was incredible. My favorite was the hamachi and the chef informed me that he has his hamachi flown in from Tsukijis in Japan. He uses different seasonings for each sushi, including lime and orange zest, different shoyus, and Kewpie mayo. The different flavors are unique but they do not overpower the taste of the fish itself. The ahi was so smooth and the cuts of fish he gave me were humongous! The chef even offered us a free black sesame ice cream at the end of our meal which was so ono! We are definitely going to be getting that the next time we come.

Be prepared for an amazingly casual yet scrumptious experience.  Sushi Murayama is tucked into a nondescript building on the 3rd floor with no exterior signage. The quality of the food and personality of the chefs here brings back familiar regulars, and word of mouth seems to make overt marketing unnecessary.  You CAN order a la carte from the menu, but the most effective way to fully experience the tour de force from the chef Murayama is to put your fate in his hands and order the omakase menu AND sit at the sushi bar.  What a tour de force is.  The chef will ask you for your personal tastes, and tailor your experience accordingly. What you get as part of the omakase may be dramatically different from the person next to you. You can cut off the omakase when you can't take any more food. In the meantime, the stream of well executed kitchen items as well as the freshest sushi and sashimi will be presented to you.  The variety and freshness of his product is truly remarkable here. My 13 course omakase included fresh scallops from Hokkaido, sea urchin from both east coast Canada and Santa Barbara, jumbo prawns from Thailand, and wagyu beef sourced from various parts of Japan. I was blown away with every course.  Do be prepared to pay anywhere from $75 to a hundred or more. It's an expensive proposition, buy well worth searching for a nondescript restaurant and paying a reasonable price for some of the best execution in Japanese cuisine.

Seriously this place is amazing. I have only been once but I can't stop raving to friends about how delicious and fresh the food here is. His omakase isn't your typical run of the game omakase set. The chef here truly picks out fishes that he believes is the best of the day and serves that to you. I asked him why certain pieces or dishes aren't in his omakase when it's always in every other restaurants set, and his response was that he doesn't serve the same fish everyday because they're not always the best the day has to offer. I didn't get uni or otoro the day I went but that didn't mean my pieces were anything else than spectacular. Every fish that was laid in front of me was so fresh and I believe was the best of the best because I can't stop thinking about the fishes and how sweet they were. His portions are also generous. My favorite dish though would have to be his shrimp tempura. A dish I think is only mediocre everywhere else, I would have to rate his as a 20 out of 10. Seriously it was that good. I still dream of the p refectory coated shrimp that was so sweet and juicy and perfectly salted. I could eat dozens of those in one sitting. Make reservations ahead of time and try to get the omakase and don't be too picky about it. He knows what he's doing and if you can't eat that much, maybe just order Ala cart.

Since I was celebrating my big 3-0 in Honolulu, Mr. Dubs made the surprising move of making a list of restaurants to try. On the top of his list was Sushi Murayama. We were so excited to check out their Omakase and experience that OMG factor that other people are raving about.  At first we were pretty excited as the sushi were fresh and delicious.  Here's what we had: - Marinated tuna w/nori - Sweet shrimp tempura - Flounder tail topped with seasalt - Saba belly - Tuna w/ fried garlic and green onions (by far our fave) - Big island abalone - Snow crab - Aji horse mackeral - Black throat snapper  A pretty solid roster you would think, right? Well, here's why this experience fell short to a 3-star review.  - The big island abalone nigiri was GROSS. It was extremely chewy to a point where it was crunchy.. exactly how you would imagine a raw abalone. I stuck the entire thing into my mouth and wanted it all to go away as quickly as possible. - I saw flies around the metal pan with the shrimp tempura. - A couple who came in after us ordered the omakase and was greeted to toro, sea scallops and a wider variety of tempura. We were only given one choice for the omakase, so I don't understand how and why this other couple would be given more premium pieces. - Lastly, part of why omakase is a fun experience is because the chefs are always friendly and knowledgeable. However, our chef prepped our omakase at the other end and never said more to us than what we were eating next.  I would definitely not recommend Sushi Murayama to any of my foodie friends.
